Dr '''Henry Howe Arnold Bemrose''' [[Fellow of the Geological Society|FGS]] (13 March 1857, [[Derby]] – 17 July 1939, Derby) was an English printer, publisher, and geologist.<ref name=Obit>{{cite journal|title=Biographical notices of mineralogists recently deceased (Eighth Series)|journal=The Mineralogical Magazine and Journal of the Mineralogical Society|date=December 1947|volume=28|issue=199|pages=179–180|url=http://www.minersoc.org/pages/Archive-MM/Volume_28/28-199-175.pdf}}</ref>

He, early in life, assumed the name of "Arnold-Bemrose" to distinguish his name from that of his father, Sir [[Henry Howe Bemrose]] (1827–1911) and, upon the death of his father, reverted to the name "Bemrose". Arnold-Bemrose graduated B.A. 1879 from [[Clare College, Cambridge]] and then entered his father's printing firm of Bemrose and Sons, where he remained active for over fifty years.<ref name=Obit/> Arnold-Bemrose received his M.A. in 1882 and his Sc.D. in 1908 from Clare College, Cambridge.<ref>{{acad|id=BMRS875HH|name=Bemrose, Henry Howe}}</ref> He was the [[Mayor of Derby]] for 1909.<ref name=Obit/> 

He published over twenty papers dealing mostly with geology, as well as the 1910 book ''Derbyshire'' on the county's geology, history, antiquities, and architecture.<ref>{{cite book|author=Arnold-Bemrose, Henry Howe|title=Derbyshire|year=1910|publisher=Cambridge University Press|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000112960}}</ref> He received the [[Murchison Medal]] in 1938.

